===Recent history===
[[File:Ocean_City_MD_Boardwalk_August_2009_1.jpg|thumb]]
[[File:Ocean_City_MD_Boardwalk_August_2009_3.jpg|thumb]]
Today, the Ocean City area continues to sprawl westward across the bay and toward [[Berlin,_Maryland|Berlin]] and [[Ocean_Pines,_Maryland|Ocean Pines]]. It is part of the Ocean Pines [[Micropolitan_Statistical_Area|Micropolitan Statistical Area]]. The resort area accommodates approximately 8 million visitors per year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ococean.com/media |title=Ocean City Maryland - Media |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Ocean City Maryland Convention and Visitors Bureau and Department of Tourism |accessdate=2011-09-06}}</ref>
 
Ocean City now extends just more than {{convert|9|mi|abbr=on}} from the southern inlet to the Delaware line. The strip now supports hotels, motels, apartment houses, shopping centers, residential communities, and condominiums. The southern tip houses the Ocean City [[Boardwalk#Ocean_City,_Maryland|Boardwalk]]. The boardwalk is the main shopping district and entertainment area of the town. The boardwalk has many prominent businesses including Fisher's Caramel Popcorn and [[Thrashers_French_Fries|Thrashers French Fries]]. Other notable boardwalk businesses are [[Dolle's_Salt_Water_Taffy|Dolle's Salt Water Taffy]], the [[Atlantic_Stand|Atlantic Stand]], and [[Dumser's_Dairyland|Dumser's Dairyland]].  The Boardwalk has two [[amusement_park|amusement park]]s, [[Trimpers_Rides|Trimpers Rides]] and The Pier, which was recently renamed [[Jolly_Roger_Amusement_Park|Jolly Roger at The Pier]], after [[Jolly_Roger_Amusement_Park|its sister uptown local amusement park]]. The downtown neighborhood, Old Town, is marked by Victorian style houses and other older buildings, many of which have been razed in recent years to construct more parking lots, hotels, and condos.

