==Geography==
[[File:Ocean_City_MD_pier_from_south.jpeg|thumb]]
Ocean City is located at {{coord|38.391526|-75.069712|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=inline}}.{{GR|1}}

According to the [[United_States_Census_Bureau|United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of {{convert|36.37|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which, {{convert|4.41|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|31.96|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name ="Gazetteer files">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United_States_Census_Bureau|United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2013-01-25}}</ref>

Ocean City is on the barrier [[Spit_(landform)|spit]] called [[Fenwick_Island_(Delaware–Maryland)|Fenwick Island]], which encompasses Ocean City, [[South_Bethany,_Delaware|South Bethany, Delaware]], and [[Fenwick_Island,_Delaware|Fenwick Island, Delaware]].  Ocean City's southern point is an [[inlet|inlet]] formed by the [[1933_Chesapeake–Potomac_hurricane|1933 Chesapeake–Potomac hurricane]].  Rainfall and tides swelled the rivers and bays surrounding Ocean City until the overflowing water cut a 50 foot [[crevasse|crevasse]] from the bay to the ocean.  Ocean City businessmen had long sought funding to create an inlet to support a harbor, so residents seized upon the opportunity and built jetties to ensure the city's land remained divided from what is now [[Assateague_Island|Assateague Island]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/eastern-shore/bal-hurricane2003,0,7880742.story|title=Reborn in a Hurricane|work=www.baltimoresun.com|publisher=[[The_Baltimore_Sun|The Baltimore Sun]]|accessdate=2009-08-31}}</ref>

===Climate===
Ocean City has a [[humid_subtropical_climate|humid subtropical climate]] ([[Köppen_climate_classification|Köppen]] ''Cfa''), with hot, humid summers, mild winters, and precipitation fairly evenly distributed throughout the year. Due to its location on the Atlantic coast, daytime temperatures in spring and summer are moderated, with an average of only 10 days annually reaching {{convert|90|°F|0}}. Conversely, in winter there is an average of 5.8 days where the temperature fails to rise above freezing. The prominence of the [[Outer_Banks|Outer Banks]] of [[North_Carolina|North Carolina]] to the south means direct hits from [[tropical_storm|tropical storm]]s and [[hurricane|hurricane]]s are rare, although they sometimes brush the area.

